To tackle this problem, we'll need to create a program in Java that reads the input as specified, applies an algorithm to determine the optimal columns to toggle with the laser to maximize the amplification factor, and outputs the result for each test case.

Here's a simple Java program that should work according to the given requirements:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class SignalAmplifier {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        int testCases = scanner.nextInt();

        for (int t = 1; t <= testCases; t++) {
            int N = scanner.nextInt(); // Rows
            int M = scanner.nextInt(); // Columns
            int K = scanner.nextInt(); // Number of times laser can be used

            int[][] amplifier = new int[N][M];
            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
                for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
                    amplifier[i][j] = scanner.nextInt();
                }
            }

            System.out.println("#" + t + " " + maxAmplificationFactor(amplifier, N, M, K));
        }

        scanner.close();
    }

    private static int maxAmplificationFactor(int[][] amplifier, int N, int M, int K) {
        int maxFactor = 0;

        // Count zeros in each row
        int[] zeroCount = new int[N];
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
                if (amplifier[i][j] == 0) {
                    zeroCount[i]++;
                }
            }
        }

        while (K > 0) {
            // Find the row with maximum number of zeros which is not yet completed (has zeros remaining)
            int maxZeros = 0;
            int rowNum = -1;
            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
                if (zeroCount[i] > maxZeros) {
                    maxZeros = zeroCount[i];
                    rowNum = i;
                }
            }

            // If no such row found or all rows have been completed, break
            if (rowNum == -1) break;

            // Find column with maximum impact (toggle the column which has a zero in the selected row)
            int colNum = -1;
            for (int j = 0; j < M; j++) {
                if (amplifier[rowNum][j] == 0) {
                    colNum = j;
                    break;
                }
            }

            // Toggle the column
            for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
                amplifier[i][colNum] ^= 1; // XOR with 1 will toggle the bit
                // Update zero count
                if (amplifier[i][colNum] == 0) {
                    zeroCount[i]++;
                } else {
                    zeroCount[i]--;
                }
            }

            K--; // Decrement the count of laser usage
        }

        // Calculate maximum amplification factor
        for (int zeros : zeroCount) {
            if (zeros == 0) {
                maxFactor++;
            }
        }

        return maxFactor;
    }
}
```

This program reads the input for T test cases, for each case it reads the size of the amplifier grid (N and M), the number of times the laser can be used (K), and then the statuses of all elements in the grid. Then it calculates the maximum amplification factor for the given grid and outputs it.

The algorithm is fairly simple and works by toggling the column with the most impact (i.e., the column which has a '0' in the row with the most '0's). It does not guarantee the optimal solution for all cases, since the problem is akin to a complex optimization problem which might require more analytical or heuristic approaches for the best solution.

